      },
      "images": {}
    },
    {
      "id": "/page/0/Text/6",
      "block_type": "Text",
      "html": "<p block-type=\"Text\">This requires <i>n</i> + 1 observations of the daily closing stock price <i>Si</i>. The factor 252 is the approximate number of business days in a year, which gives an annualized variance. Also note that this formula assumes the mean of the returns to be zero. This means that it is distinct from the statistical variance of the returns. The mean of returns is typically small and setting it to zero makes returns on variance swaps additive over time. Using log returns to measure variance makes this formula compatible with the standard Black–Scholes option pricing formula.</p>",
      "page": 489,
      "polygon": [
        [
          75.517578125,
          329.1452941894531
        ],
        [
          285.2292175292969,
          329.1452941894531
